{"title_page": "Charles F. Ashley", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n | name            =  Charles F. Ashley\n | state_house     =  Alabama\n | district        =  [[Alabama House of Representatives, District 1|1st]]\n | term_start      =  November 3, 1982\n | term_end        =  November 9, 1983\n | predecessor     =  [[John E. Higginbotham]]\n | successor       =  [[Nelson R. Starkey Jr.]]\n | birth_date      = November 9, 1936\n | birth_place     = Alabama, USA\n | death_date      = {{death date and age|2011|03|04|1936|11|09}}\n | death_place     = \n | party           = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n | spouse          = Louise Canerday Ashley (1938-?)\n | parents         = Charles Ashley Jr.<br/><small>(1913-1956)</small><br/>Mamie Ludell Stevenson<br/><small>(1915-2004)</small>\n | relations       = John T. Ashley (brother)<br/>Bob Ashley (brother)\n | children        = Freddie Ashley (son)<br/>Billy Ashley (son)<br/>Alyssa Ashley (daughter)\n}}\n\n'''Charles F.  Ashley''' (November 9, 1936 - March 4, 2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislature.state.al.us/aliswww/history/past_legislators.html|website=legislature.state.al.us|title=Past Legislators|accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/104761329|website=findagrave.com|title=Charles F. Ashley (1936-2011)|accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref> was an American politician who served in the [[Alabama House of Representatives]] from 1982\u20131983.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=82072|website=ourcampaigns.com|title=Ashley, Charles|accessdate=March 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nAshley was born on November 9, 1936 in [[Alabama]] to Charles Ashley Jr. and Mamie Ludell Stevenson. His father died when Charles was around 20 years old. At some point, he married Louise Canerday Ashley and had 3 children. He died on March 4, 2011 at the age of 74. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/name/charles-ashley-obituary?pid=149093546&page=2|website=legacy.com|title=Charles Ashley Obituary|accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n===1982 Election===\nAshley was one of 3 candidates running in the Democratic primary. He won with 54% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=525780|website=ourcampaigns.com|title=1982 Democratic Primary|accessdate=March 30, 2019}}</ref> It was only him and an Independent running for this seat because no Republican candidates have even ran since the 1966 election. He won the General Election with 76% of the votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=216863|website=ourcampaigns.com|title=1982 General Election|accessdate=March 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ashley, Charles}}\n[[Category:Alabama Democrats]]\n[[Category:Members of the Alabama House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n\n{{Alabama-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n | name            =  Charles F. Ashley\n | state_house     =  Alabama\n | district        =  [[Alabama House of Representatives, District 1|1st]]\n | term_start      =  November 3, 1982\n | term_end        =  November 9, 1983\n | predecessor     =  [[John E. Higginbotham]]\n | successor       =  [[Nelson R. Starkey Jr.]]\n | birth_date      = November 9, 1936\n | birth_place     = Alabama, USA\n | death_date      = {{death date and age|2011|03|04|1936|11|09}}\n | death_place     = \n | party           = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n | spouse          = Louise Canerday Ashley (1938-?)\n | parents         = Charles Ashley Jr.<br/><small>(1913-1956)</small><br/>Mamie Ludell Stevenson<br/><small>(1915-2004)</small>\n | relations       = John T. Ashley (brother)<br/>Bob Ashley (brother)\n | children        = Freddie Ashley (son)<br/>Billy Ashley (son)<br/>Alyssa Ashley (daughter)\n}}\n\n'''Charles F.  Ashley''' (November 9, 1936 - March 4, 2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislature.state.al.us/aliswww/history/past_legislators.html|website=legislature.state.al.us|title=Past Legislators|accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/104761329|website=findagrave.com|title=Charles F. Ashley (1936-2011)|accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref> was an American politician who served in the [[Alabama House of Representatives]] from 1982-1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=82072|website=ourcampaigns.com|title=Ashley, Charles|accessdate=March 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nAshley was born on November 9, 1936 in [[Alabama]] to Charles Ashley Jr. and Mamie Ludell Stevenson. His father died when Charles was around 20 years old. At some point, he married Louise Canerday Ashley and had 3 children. He died on March 4, 2011 at the age of 74. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/name/charles-ashley-obituary?pid=149093546&page=2|website=legacy.com|title=Charles Ashley Obituary|accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n===1982 Election===\nAshley was one of 3 candidates running in the Democratic primary. He won with 54% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=525780|website=ourcampaigns.com|title=1982 Democratic Primary|accessdate=March 30, 2019}}</ref> It was only him and an Independent running for this seat because no Republican candidates have even ran since the 1966 election. He won the General Election with 76% of the votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=216863|website=ourcampaigns.com|title=1982 General Election|accessdate=March 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ashley, Charles}}\n[[Category:Alabama Democrats]]\n[[Category:Members of the Alabama House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n\n{{Alabama-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1982-1983 \u2192 1982\u20131983", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_F._Ashley"}
{"title_page": "California Theatre (San Francisco)", "text_new": "{{Infobox theatre\n| name               = California Theatre\n| image              = California Theatre San Francisco ca 1870.jpg\n| image_size         = 300px\n| image_alt          = \n| caption            = California Theatre ca. 1870\n| image_map          = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n| address            = 414 Bush St.\n| city               = San Francisco\n| country            = \n| designation        = California Theatre\n| latitude           = \n| longitude          = \n| architect          = [[Samuel Charles Bugbee|S. C. Bugbee & Son]]\n| owner              = Bank of California\n| tenant             = \n| operator           = William Ralston\n| capacity           = \n| type               = \n| opened             = January 18, 1869\n| reopened           = \n| yearsactive        = \n| rebuilt            = May 18, 1889\n| closed             = \n| demolished         = 1906\n| othernames         = \n| production         = \n| currentuse         = \n| embedded           = {{designation list|embed=yes|designation1=California|designation1_number=86<ref name=CHL/>}}\n| website            = \n}}\n\n[[Image:William Chapman Ralston.jpg|thumb|100px|William Ralston]]\n[[Image:California Theatre Ruins 1906.jpg|thumb|100px|California Theatre ruins 1906]]\n'''The California Theatre''' was located at 414 (now 440) Bush Street, [[San Francisco]].<ref> Lois Rather, Bonanza Theater, (private publishing, Rather Press, 1977), 23-25 </ref> <ref>K. Baedeker (1904) ''The United States: with an excursion into Mexico''</ref> It was built in 1869 by [[William Ralston]], at that time the treasurer of the [[Bank of California]]. [[Samuel Charles Bugbee|S. C. Bugbee & Son]] were the architects and the theatre cost $250, 000 to build.<ref name=wilmeth/><ref group=Note>Another source puts the figure at $150,000. (ref.''The Oxford Companion to American theatre'' (2004)</ref> The original theatre was demolished and rebuilt in 1889. It was destroyed in the [[San Francisco earthquake of 1906]]. The former site (north side of Bush Street, between Kearny and Grant) is now a [[California Historical Landmark]], with a historical marker commemorating the theatre and its artists.<ref name=CHL/> The original theater encompassed 165 feet of frontage, 117 feet in depth, resting on 4 1/2 foot foundation walls; a handsome building with a dress circle, gallery and 51 foot ceiling space in the interior auditorium. <ref> Rather, Bonanza Theater, 26.</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nRalston, and his partner's decision to build the theater was inspired by the acting of [[John Edward McCullough|John McCullough]] and [[Lawrence Barrett]], whom he felt deserved a theater of their own to showcase their talent. Their belief that it would prove a lucrative investment was proven right. The theatre was successful beyond wildest expectations. The Corinthian-style temple of amusement, which had cost a quarter of a million dollars,  opened on January 18, 1869 with a performance of [[Edward Bulwer-Lytton, 1st Baron Lytton|Bulwer-Lytton]]'s play ''Money''. <ref> Rather, Bonanza Theater, 29.</ref> <ref name=wilmeth>Don B. Wilmeth (2007) ''The Cambridge Guide to American Theatre'', Cambridge University Press; 2 edition {{ISBN|0521835380}}</ref> it was the leading theater in the city until its demolition in 1888. There were elaborate murals of San Francisco painted by local artist [[Gideon Jacques Denny|G.J. Denny]] and a panoramic view of San Francisco Bay entitled \"Entrance to the Golden Gate,\" on the drop curtain. The theater claimed to be the first on the West Coast to use calcium light ([[limelight]]) with parabolic reflectors, aimed from the house, to light up the stage.<ref name=smith/>\n\nOn the first anniversary of the theater's opening, a Scandinavian bandleader had the following to say,\n\n<blockquote>The first year [1869-1870] the California Theatre cleared $100,000. On the evening of our first anniversary, Mr. Barrett stood at the stage door and invited every single individual belonging to the theatre, saying that after the performance we should all meet up in Pacific Hall on the second floor of the California Theatre building, facing Bush street. Upon coming into the hall we were surprised with a large banquet table set in the form of \u201cT\u201d and furnished from the best caterer, Maison-Doree, at $5 a piece.<ref>''Musical and Theatrical New, San Francisco'' (1922) \"The Journal of August Wetterman\", California State Library, Sacramento</ref></blockquote>\n\n\nButtressed by good financial prospects due to a mini-boom in mining in Nevada, the California Theater enjoyed a blockbuster premiere season. With [[Annette Ince]] as leading lady, and a fine supporting cast largely recruited from rival manager [[Thomas Maguire (impresario)|Thomas Maguire]], the California hosted plays ranging from Shakespeare through melodrama and comedy. <ref> Carolyn Grattan Eichin, ''From San Francisco Eastward; Victorian Theater in the American West'', (University of Nevada Press, 2020), 116,135,245n112</ref> Comedian [[John E. Owens]] became the first nationally known star to perform at the California on tour, followed by East Coast sensation [[Charlotte Thompson (actress)|Charlotte Thompson]].<ref> Eichin, ''From San Francisco Eastward'', 116, 179,126</ref>. At the end of the first season, the large cast and crew of the California traveled to [[Virginia City, Nevada]] to perform for over a month at [[Piper's Opera House]] in popular shows including ''Sea of Ice''. <ref> Eichin, From San Francisco Eastward, 126-127</ref>. By January 3, 1870 the theater had offered its 300th performance with McCullough and Barrett in an intense rivalry highlighted by the fact that McCullough had appeared in twenty-seven leading roles to Barrett's ten. <ref> Rather, ''Bonanza Theater'', 51-52, 56 </ref> By mid-1870 Barrett took a leave of absence and returned to New York City, eventually selling his financial interest to John McCullough. Barrett returned to the California Theatre as a star, not a manager, in 1872 as part of a western tour. <ref> Rather, ''Bonanza Theater'', 59</ref>, Eichin, ''From San Francisco Eastward'', 106-108, 128.</ref>\n\nThe theater enjoyed exceptional years in the mid-1870s due to good economic times following the discovery of the discrete big bonanza ore chamber on the Comstock Lode. Coupled with recession on the East Coast, many recognized actors and actresses trekked west to play the California. The cavalcade of stars included [[Dion Boucicault]] in his own creations, [[Lotta Crabtree]], [[William J. Florence]], [[Elizabeth Crocker Bowers]], [[Agnes Booth]] and her husband [[Junius Booth, Jr.]], [[Edwin Booth]], [[Katherine Rodgers Randolph]] and others.<ref> Carolyn Grattan Eichin, ''From San Francisco Eastward:'' ''Victorian Theater in the American West,'' (Reno: University of Nevada Press, 2020),161-184.</ref> In spite of the theatre's success, the Bank of California, which owned the theatre, failed in 1875, as the National Panic of 1873 challenged the financial picture after the short-lived silver boom. Soon thereafter, Ralston went swimming and drowned, leading to speculation that he might have committed suicide.<ref group=Note>This is somewhat belied by the evidence that he was seen thrashing about in the water at the time of his drowning.</ref> Although the theatre then went into a decline, it had broken manager Thomas Maguire's hegemony in the western theater world. <ref> Carolyn Grattan Eichin, ''From San Francisco Eastward: Victorian'' ''Theater in the American West'', (Reno: University of Nevada Press, 2020), 171, 183-4 </ref>.<ref name=smith>James R. Smith (2004) ''San Francisco's Lost Landmarks'', Linden Publishing {{ISBN|1884995446}}</ref>\n\nAlthough San Francisco did not host full operas during the mid-1800s, <ref> Eichin, ''From San Francisco Eastward'', 171-2</ref> <ref> George Martin, ''Verdi at the Golden Gate, Opera and San Francisco During the Golden Years'' (Berkeley: University of California Press, 1993), 162, 179, 199</ref>, singers presented operatic music on occasion. The theatre hosted soprano [[Inez Fabbri]] on occasion, as well as [[Nellie Melba]].<ref name=NYT>''New York Times'' (May 9, 1898) \"Melba in a Panic\"</ref><ref group=Note>Melba's performance was cut short by a fire in the neighboring building causing a stampede for the exit by San Francisco's Social Register who were there ''en masse'' and decked out for the occasion, leaving behind furs and other valuable belongings in the pandemonium, with an estimated value of $4000.[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1898/05/09/102561129.pdf]</ref>\n\n===The new California Theatre===\n\nA new California Theatre,<ref name=\"wilmeth\"/> opened on the site on May 18, 1889,<ref name=electric>''The Electrical World'' Vol.14 (1889) Digitized by Google Books</ref> but was destroyed in the 1906 earthquake and fire, but it never regained its former status after Ralston's death in 1875 and McCullough's departure in 1877.<ref>''The Oxford Companion to American Theatre'', 3rd edn. (2004) G. Bordman, T.S. Hischak eds., Oxford University Press {{ISBN|0195169867}}</ref> During the 1880s San Francisco hosted a change in theater business strategies from stock companies to the use of combination companies, in part, a response to poorer economic times with the demise of silver mining. <ref> Eichin, From San Francisco Eastward, 114-138</ref>. The new California theatre was the first on the West Coast to be lighted exclusively with electricity.<ref name=electric/>\n\nThe periodical, ''The Electrical World'',  had the following to say about the new theatre,\n\n<blockquote>The new temple of [[Thespis]] is situated on the site of the famous old California Theatre. It is perfectly fire-proof, and has 19 exits. The main entrance, on Bush street, is formed by a Roman arch of massive proportions and striking design. The vestibule is rectangular in shape, is finished in antique oak panelling, with pilasters and arabesques, and is lighted by thirty-two 16 candle-power lamps and an electrolier of eight 82's. In the beautiful foyer is another large electrolier.\n<br/><br/>\nIn the auditorium, behind the eight proscenium boxes, with dome-shaped canopies supported by columns, rise arches of Indian fretwork carrying pillars surmounted by 88 candle-power lamps enclosed in opalescent globes shaped like pineapples. The ceiling consists of three concave divisions extending from wall to wall parallel with the front of the stage, gradually rising upward, and separated by narrow panels or chords. It is crossed by four bands of dark color, in which, as well as in the chords and fantastic tracery of the decorations, are set numbers of lamps. From the ceiling, over the parquet and near the boxes, depend three rich electroliers similar in design to those throughout the house, formed by a centre fixture of opalescent glass held in cast metal work, with four pendants of the same shape hanging by chains attached to arms radiating from the stem of the fixture. All the electroliers were specially designed by J. M. Wood, of Chicago, the architect.\n<br/><br/>\nThroughout the house the decorations are so designed that lamps in the midst of bands of flowers, dados and carvings, not only afford light, but add hitherto unknown features to the general ornamentation. At the back of the metal and plastic tracery of the boxes, balcony and gallery, panels of cathedral glass are inserted, which soften the radiance of 16 candle-power lamps set behind, and give to the railings the effect of carvings thrown into relief by mellow light. For producing winter and moonlight effects, and as a substitute for calcium light, six movable bunch lights, with silvered reflectors, are provided.\n<br/><br/>\nThe rheostats, which control all the lamps in the house, are of novel design. They are divided into six parts, which are in connection with six step-by-step switches, capable of being operated rapidly and positively. The handles of the switches can be locked to a shaft which runs through all; by tightening the handles of the switches to the shaft every part of the house can be dimmed at once, and by loosening any number, any portions can be regulated at the will of the switch-man. Being equally divided, one-half the lamps in the auditorium can gradually be turned down while the other half is being lighted, producing a fine blending effect. This is probably the only theatre in the country where the switches are so arranged.<ref name=electric/></blockquote>\n\n===Landmark===\nIn 1933, the site was registered as [[California Historical Landmark]] #86.<ref name=CHL>{{cite ohp|86|California Theatre|2012-10-14}}</ref> The landmark marker, located at 430 Bush Street, mentions the January 18, 1869 opening date, and lists a number of artists who played there.<ref name=CHL/>\n\n==Notable artists==\n{{colbegin|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Edwin Adams (actor)|Edwin Adams]]<ref name=CHL/>\n*[[Lawrence Barrett]]<ref name=CHL/>\n*[[Adele Blood]]<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=19360914&id=v7MhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iZsFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3918,2733489 ''Reading Eagle'' (Sep 14, 1936) \"Stage Beauty Ends Life With Bullet\"]</ref>\n*[[Edwin Booth]]<ref name=CHL/>\n*[[Hobart Bosworth]]<ref>[http://califtheatre.com/testimonial-benefit-to-hobart-bosworth-california-theatre-july-14-1905/ \"Testimonial Benefit to Hobart Bosworth\"]{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, California Theatre, July 14, 1905</ref>\n*[[Lotta Crabtree]]<ref name=CHL/>\n*[[Willie Edouin]]<ref name=CHL/>\n*[[Henry Edwards (entomologist)|Harry Edwards]]<ref name=CHL/>\n*[[Inez Fabbri]]<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vmyJniA_1f4C&pg=PA273 |page=273 |title=The Arts of the Prima Donna in the Long Nineteenth Century |first=Rachel |last=Cowgill |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2012 |isbn=0195365887}}</ref>\n*[[John Edward McCullough|John McCullough]]<ref name=CHL/>\n*[[Nellie Melba]]<ref name=NYT/>\n*[[Helena Modjeska]]<ref>[http://muse.jhu.edu/login?auth=0&type=summary&url=/journals/theatre_journal/v062/62.3.holmgren.pdf \"The Art of Playing Patriot: The Polish Stardom of Helena Modjeska\"]</ref>\n*[[Adelaide Neilson]]<ref name=CHL/>\n*[[John T. Raymond]]<ref name=CHL/>\n{{colend}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|37|47|27.3|N|122|24|17.4|W|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Theatres in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Event venues established in 1869]]\n[[Category:Demolished theatres in California]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures burned in the 1906 San Francisco earthquake]]\n[[Category:1869 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox theatre\n| name               = California Theatre\n| image              = California Theatre San Francisco ca 1870.jpg\n| image_size         = 300px\n| image_alt          = \n| caption            = California Theatre ca. 1870\n| image_map          = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n| address            = 414 Bush St.\n| city               = San Francisco\n| country            = \n| designation        = California Theatre\n| latitude           = \n| longitude          = \n| architect          = [[Samuel Charles Bugbee|S. C. Bugbee & Son]]\n| owner              = Bank of California\n| tenant             = \n| operator           = William Ralston\n| capacity           = \n| type               = \n| opened             = January 18, 1869\n| reopened           = \n| yearsactive        = \n| rebuilt            = May 18, 1889\n| closed             = \n| demolished         = 1906\n| othernames         = \n| production         = \n| currentuse         = \n| embedded           = {{designation list|embed=yes|designation1=California|designation1_number=86<ref name=CHL/>}}\n| website            = \n}}\n\n[[Image:William Chapman Ralston.jpg|thumb|100px|William Ralston]]\n[[Image:California Theatre Ruins 1906.jpg|thumb|100px|California Theatre ruins 1906]]\n'''The California Theatre''' was located at 414 (now 440) Bush Street, [[San Francisco]].<ref> Lois Rather, Bonanza Theater, (private publishing, Rather Press, 1977), 23-25 </ref> <ref>K. Baedeker (1904) ''The United States: with an excursion into Mexico''</ref> It was built in 1869 by [[William Ralston]], at that time the treasurer of the [[Bank of California]]. [[Samuel Charles Bugbee|S. C. Bugbee & Son]] were the architects and the theatre cost $250, 000 to build.<ref name=wilmeth/><ref group=Note>Another source puts the figure at $150,000. (ref.''The Oxford Companion to American theatre'' (2004)</ref> The original theatre was demolished and rebuilt in 1889. It was destroyed in the [[San Francisco earthquake of 1906]]. The former site (north side of Bush Street, between Kearny and Grant) is now a [[California Historical Landmark]], with a historical marker commemorating the theatre and its artists.<ref name=CHL/> The original theater encompassed 165 feet of frontage, 117 feet in depth, resting on 4 1/2 foot foundation walls; a handsome building with a dress circle, gallery and 51 foot ceiling space in the interior auditorium. <ref> Rather, Bonanza Theater, 26.</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nRalston, and his partner's decision to build the theater was inspired by the acting of [[John Edward McCullough|John McCullough]] and [[Lawrence Barrett]], whom he felt deserved a theater of their own to showcase their talent. Their belief that it would prove a lucrative investment was proven right. The theatre was successful beyond wildest expectations. The Corinthian-style temple of amusement, which had cost a quarter of a million dollars,  opened on January 18, 1869 with a performance of [[Edward Bulwer-Lytton, 1st Baron Lytton|Bulwer-Lytton]]'s play ''Money''. <ref> Rather, Bonanza Theater, 29.</ref> <ref name=wilmeth>Don B. Wilmeth (2007) ''The Cambridge Guide to American Theatre'', Cambridge University Press; 2 edition {{ISBN|0521835380}}</ref> it was the leading theater in the city until its demolition in 1888. There were elaborate murals of San Francisco painted by local artist [[Gideon Jacques Denny|G.J. Denny]] and a panoramic view of San Francisco Bay entitled \"Entrance to the Golden Gate,\" on the drop curtain. The theater claimed to be the first on the West Coast to use calcium light ([[limelight]]) with parabolic reflectors, aimed from the house, to light up the stage.<ref name=smith/>\n\nOn the first anniversary of the theater's opening, a Scandinavian bandleader had the following to say,\n\n<blockquote>The first year [1869-1870] the California Theatre cleared $100,000. On the evening of our first anniversary, Mr. Barrett stood at the stage door and invited every single individual belonging to the theatre, saying that after the performance we should all meet up in Pacific Hall on the second floor of the California Theatre building, facing Bush street. Upon coming into the hall we were surprised with a large banquet table set in the form of \u201cT\u201d and furnished from the best caterer, Maison-Doree, at $5 a piece.<ref>''Musical and Theatrical New, San Francisco'' (1922) \"The Journal of August Wetterman\", California State Library, Sacramento</ref></blockquote>\n\n\nButtressed by good financial prospects due to a mini-boom in mining in Nevada, the California Theater enjoyed a blockbuster premiere season. With [[Annette Ince]] as leading lady, and a fine supporting cast largely recruited from rival manager [[Thomas Maguire (impresario)|Thomas Maguire]], the California hosted plays ranging from Shakespeare through melodrama and comedy. <ref> Carolyn Grattan Eichin, ''From San Francisco Eastward; Victorian Theater in the American West'', (University of Nevada Press, 2020), 116,135,245n112</ref> Comedian [[John E. Owens]] became the first nationally known star to perform at the California on tour, followed by East Coast sensation [[Charlotte Thompson (actress)|Charlotte Thompson]].<ref> Eichin, ''From San Francisco Eastward'', 116, 179,126</ref>. At the end of the first season, the large cast and crew of the California traveled to [[Virginia City, Nevada]] to perform for over a month at [[Piper's Opera House]] in popular shows including ''Sea of Ice''. <ref> Eichin, From San Francisco Eastward, 126-127</ref>.\n\nThe theater enjoyed exceptional years in the mid-1870s due to good economic times following the discovery of the discrete big bonanza ore chamber on the Comstock Lode. Coupled with recession on the East Coast, many recognized actors and actresses trekked west to play the California. The cavalcade of stars included [[Dion Boucicault]] in his own creations, [[Lotta Crabtree]], [[William J. Florence]], [[Elizabeth Crocker Bowers]], [[Agnes Booth]] and her husband [[Junius Booth, Jr.]], [[Edwin Booth]], [[Katherine Rodgers Randolph]] and others.<ref> Carolyn Grattan Eichin, ''From San Francisco Eastward:'' ''Victorian Theater in the American West,'' (Reno: University of Nevada Press, 2020),161-184.</ref> In spite of the theatre's success, the Bank of California, which owned the theatre, failed in 1875, as the National Panic of 1873 challenged the financial picture after the short-lived silver boom. Soon thereafter, Ralston went swimming and drowned, leading to speculation that he might have committed suicide.<ref group=Note>This is somewhat belied by the evidence that he was seen thrashing about in the water at the time of his drowning.</ref> Although the theatre then went into a decline, it had broken manager Thomas Maguire's hegemony in the western theater world. <ref> Carolyn Grattan Eichin, ''From San Francisco Eastward: Victorian'' ''Theater in the American West'', (Reno: University of Nevada Press, 2020), 171, 183-4 </ref>.<ref name=smith>James R. Smith (2004) ''San Francisco's Lost Landmarks'', Linden Publishing {{ISBN|1884995446}}</ref>\n\nAlthough San Francisco did not host full operas during the mid-1800s, <ref> Eichin, ''From San Francisco Eastward'', 171-2</ref> <ref> George Martin, ''Verdi at the Golden Gate, Opera and San Francisco During the Golden Years'' (Berkeley: University of California Press, 1993), 162, 179, 199</ref>, singers presented operatic music on occasion. The theatre hosted soprano [[Inez Fabbri]] on occasion, as well as [[Nellie Melba]].<ref name=NYT>''New York Times'' (May 9, 1898) \"Melba in a Panic\"</ref><ref group=Note>Melba's performance was cut short by a fire in the neighboring building causing a stampede for the exit by San Francisco's Social Register who were there ''en masse'' and decked out for the occasion, leaving behind furs and other valuable belongings in the pandemonium, with an estimated value of $4000.[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1898/05/09/102561129.pdf]</ref>\n\n===The new California Theatre===\n\nA new California Theatre,<ref name=\"wilmeth\"/> opened on the site on May 18, 1889,<ref name=electric>''The Electrical World'' Vol.14 (1889) Digitized by Google Books</ref> but was destroyed in the 1906 earthquake and fire, but it never regained its former status after Ralston's death in 1875 and McCullough's departure in 1877.<ref>''The Oxford Companion to American Theatre'', 3rd edn. (2004) G. Bordman, T.S. Hischak eds., Oxford University Press {{ISBN|0195169867}}</ref> During the 1880s San Francisco hosted a change in theater business strategies from stock companies to the use of combination companies, in part, a response to poorer economic times with the demise of silver mining. <ref> Eichin, From San Francisco Eastward, 114-138</ref>. The new California theatre was the first on the West Coast to be lighted exclusively with electricity.<ref name=electric/>\n\nThe periodical, ''The Electrical World'',  had the following to say about the new theatre,\n\n<blockquote>The new temple of [[Thespis]] is situated on the site of the famous old California Theatre. It is perfectly fire-proof, and has 19 exits. The main entrance, on Bush street, is formed by a Roman arch of massive proportions and striking design. The vestibule is rectangular in shape, is finished in antique oak panelling, with pilasters and arabesques, and is lighted by thirty-two 16 candle-power lamps and an electrolier of eight 82's. In the beautiful foyer is another large electrolier.\n<br/><br/>\nIn the auditorium, behind the eight proscenium boxes, with dome-shaped canopies supported by columns, rise arches of Indian fretwork carrying pillars surmounted by 88 candle-power lamps enclosed in opalescent globes shaped like pineapples. The ceiling consists of three concave divisions extending from wall to wall parallel with the front of the stage, gradually rising upward, and separated by narrow panels or chords. It is crossed by four bands of dark color, in which, as well as in the chords and fantastic tracery of the decorations, are set numbers of lamps. From the ceiling, over the parquet and near the boxes, depend three rich electroliers similar in design to those throughout the house, formed by a centre fixture of opalescent glass held in cast metal work, with four pendants of the same shape hanging by chains attached to arms radiating from the stem of the fixture. All the electroliers were specially designed by J. M. Wood, of Chicago, the architect.\n<br/><br/>\nThroughout the house the decorations are so designed that lamps in the midst of bands of flowers, dados and carvings, not only afford light, but add hitherto unknown features to the general ornamentation. At the back of the metal and plastic tracery of the boxes, balcony and gallery, panels of cathedral glass are inserted, which soften the radiance of 16 candle-power lamps set behind, and give to the railings the effect of carvings thrown into relief by mellow light. For producing winter and moonlight effects, and as a substitute for calcium light, six movable bunch lights, with silvered reflectors, are provided.\n<br/><br/>\nThe rheostats, which control all the lamps in the house, are of novel design. They are divided into six parts, which are in connection with six step-by-step switches, capable of being operated rapidly and positively. The handles of the switches can be locked to a shaft which runs through all; by tightening the handles of the switches to the shaft every part of the house can be dimmed at once, and by loosening any number, any portions can be regulated at the will of the switch-man. Being equally divided, one-half the lamps in the auditorium can gradually be turned down while the other half is being lighted, producing a fine blending effect. This is probably the only theatre in the country where the switches are so arranged.<ref name=electric/></blockquote>\n\n===Landmark===\nIn 1933, the site was registered as [[California Historical Landmark]] #86.<ref name=CHL>{{cite ohp|86|California Theatre|2012-10-14}}</ref> The landmark marker, located at 430 Bush Street, mentions the January 18, 1869 opening date, and lists a number of artists who played there.<ref name=CHL/>\n\n==Notable artists==\n{{colbegin|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Edwin Adams (actor)|Edwin Adams]]<ref name=CHL/>\n*[[Lawrence Barrett]]<ref name=CHL/>\n*[[Adele Blood]]<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=19360914&id=v7MhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iZsFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3918,2733489 ''Reading Eagle'' (Sep 14, 1936) \"Stage Beauty Ends Life With Bullet\"]</ref>\n*[[Edwin Booth]]<ref name=CHL/>\n*[[Hobart Bosworth]]<ref>[http://califtheatre.com/testimonial-benefit-to-hobart-bosworth-california-theatre-july-14-1905/ \"Testimonial Benefit to Hobart Bosworth\"]{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, California Theatre, July 14, 1905</ref>\n*[[Lotta Crabtree]]<ref name=CHL/>\n*[[Willie Edouin]]<ref name=CHL/>\n*[[Henry Edwards (entomologist)|Harry Edwards]]<ref name=CHL/>\n*[[Inez Fabbri]]<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vmyJniA_1f4C&pg=PA273 |page=273 |title=The Arts of the Prima Donna in the Long Nineteenth Century |first=Rachel |last=Cowgill |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2012 |isbn=0195365887}}</ref>\n*[[John Edward McCullough|John McCullough]]<ref name=CHL/>\n*[[Nellie Melba]]<ref name=NYT/>\n*[[Helena Modjeska]]<ref>[http://muse.jhu.edu/login?auth=0&type=summary&url=/journals/theatre_journal/v062/62.3.holmgren.pdf \"The Art of Playing Patriot: The Polish Stardom of Helena Modjeska\"]</ref>\n*[[Adelaide Neilson]]<ref name=CHL/>\n*[[John T. Raymond]]<ref name=CHL/>\n{{colend}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|37|47|27.3|N|122|24|17.4|W|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Theatres in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Event venues established in 1869]]\n[[Category:Demolished theatres in California]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures burned in the 1906 San Francisco earthquake]]\n[[Category:1869 establishments in California]]\n", "name_user": "Alonealone1856", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/California_Theatre_(San_Francisco)"}
{"title_page": "The Tank (theater)", "text_new": "{{Infobox venue\n| name                   = The Tank\n| image = The Tank exterior, September 2018.jpg\n| image_alt=A yellow brick building with two double glass doors, one to the left, the other to the right, runs out of the frame at the top. A person is entering through the left glass doors. A black and white banner hangs from the second story with The Tank's logo and the words \"THE TANK\".\n| image_caption= The Tank's entrance (left), 2018\n| logo_image             = The Tank logo.jpg\n| logo_caption           = The Tank's logo\n| address                = 312 West 36th Street, Manhattan, New York\n| coordinates            = {{Coord|40.7535298|-73.9932606|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} \n| type                   = [[Off-Off-Broadway]]\n| genre                  = Dance, theater, music, film, comedy\n| opened                 = {{Start date|2003|05}} \n| website                =  {{URL|thetanknyc.org}}\n}}\n'''The Tank''' is a nonprofit [[Off-Off-Broadway]] performance venue and producer in Manhattan, New York. The organization was founded in May 2003 and has since moved several times, currently residing on 36th Street. The Tank presents art across several disciplines (comedy, dance, theater, music, film), produced at no fee for use of the venue to the presenting artists. In addition to its space in Manhattan, The Tank has produced shows performed elsewhere throughout New York City, collectively presenting over 800 performances each year. Programming at the theater is currently suspended due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].\n\n==History==\nThe Tank was founded in May 2003 in [[Manhattan]], New York, by eight artists, all recent college graduates in their mid-20s.<ref name=\"rail\">{{cite news|last1=Hodges|first1=Mary Love|title=Spotlight on The Tank|url=http://brooklynrail.org/2010/02/dance/spotlight-on-the-tank|accessdate=January 27, 2017|work=[[The Brooklyn Rail]]|date=February 3, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512063126/http://brooklynrail.org/2010/02/dance/spotlight-on-the-tank|archivedate=May 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"harv\">{{cite news|last1=Lambert|first1=Craig|title=Avant-Garde Incubator|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/2007/03/avant-garde-incubator.html|accessdate=January 28, 2017|work=[[Harvard Magazine]]|date=March\u2013April 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809010232/http://harvardmagazine.com/2007/03/avant-garde-incubator.html|archivedate=August 9, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"spirit\">{{cite news|title=Downtown Edge in Midtown Venue|last1=Eichna|first1=Charlotte|work=West Side Spirit|date=June 17, 2004|page=26}}</ref> Its founders, mostly graduates of [[Yale University]], [[Oberlin College]], and [[Harvard University]], included playwright [[Amy Herzog]], playwright and director [[Alex Timbers]], Justin Krebs, Rachel Levy, Mike Rosenthal, and Randy Bell, who collectively expressed the goal of offering young artists across disciplines the space to create work in the center of New York City.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref name=\"harv\" /><ref name=\"spirit\" /><ref name=\"theasy2013\">{{cite news|title=The Tank: A Theasy Interview with Josh Luxenberg, curator of the Flint & Tinder theater series at The Tank|url=http://www.theasy.com/FeaturedArtist/thetank.php|accessdate=January 27, 2017|work=Theatre Is Easy|date=June 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151013063555/http://www.theasy.com/FeaturedArtist/thetank.php|archivedate=October 13, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"trib\">{{cite news|title=Subterranean 'Tank' Hosts New Music|last1=Pinto|first1=Nick|page=43|date=February 2008|work=[[The Tribeca Trib]]|accessdate=June 27, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908003153/http://www.tribecatrib.com/news/newsfeb08/Tank.html|url=http://www.tribecatrib.com/news/newsfeb08/Tank.html|archivedate=September 8, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe organization was first housed on [[42nd Street (Manhattan)|42nd Street]] between [[Ninth Avenue (Manhattan)|Ninth]] and [[Tenth Avenue (Manhattan)|Tenth]] Avenues.<ref name=\"spirit\" /> The Tank leased the space on a month-to-month basis from a landlord who intended to sell the building in which the theater was housed, and within 10 months, they had repaid their startup loans. The company derived its name from the architecture of its first space: three large windows overlooking 42nd Street led to someone calling the space The Fishtank and later the ''Fish'' was dropped in favor of The Tank.<ref name=\"harv\" /><ref name=\"spirit\" /> By 2006, the company had moved twice and by 2007, it had won an unsolicited grant of $10,000 from the [[Carnegie Corporation of New York]] and was receiving money from the Lower Manhattan Cultural Council.<ref name=\"harv\" /> The Tank's third location, into which it moved in 2006, was on [[Church Street (Manhattan)|Church Street]] in the [[Tribeca]] neighborhood, where the organization shared space with [[Collective:Unconscious]] as late as 2008.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref name=\"harv\" /><ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Williams|editor1-first=James R.|title=Inside New York 2008|date=2007|publisher=Inside New York|location=New York City|isbn=978-1892768407|page=158|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZtY1xdbFJz0C&pg=PA158}}</ref>\n\nBy 2010, The Tank had returned to Manhattan's midtown [[Theater District, Manhattan|Theater District]], occupying the [[Davenport Theatre]] on 45th Street between [[Eighth Avenue (Manhattan)|Eighth]] and Ninth Avenues.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=La Rocco |first1=Claudia |title=A Long Swim Looking for Laughs |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/06/theater/reviews/the-umbrella-plays-at-the-tank.html |accessdate=March 27, 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 5, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328001030/https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/06/theater/reviews/the-umbrella-plays-at-the-tank.html |archivedate=March 28, 2019}}</ref> The Tank had moved to 46th Street by 2013, where it resided until 2017.<ref name=\"theasy2013\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Heins|first1=Scott|title=5 Fun Things To Do In NYC This Week|url=http://gothamist.com/2017/01/16/5_things_jan_2017.php|accessdate=January 28, 2017|work=[[Gothamist]]|date=January 16, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129015925/http://gothamist.com/2017/01/16/5_things_jan_2017.php|archivedate=January 29, 2017}}</ref> That year, The Tank signed a ten-year, $18,000/month lease on and moved to a two-stage venue on 36th Street, the former home of Abingdon Theatre Company, with one 56-seat [[black box theater]] and one 98-seat [[Proscenium|proscenium theater]].<ref name=\"tm move\">{{cite news|last1=Fujishima|first1=Kenji|title=The Tank Announces New Season, New Home|url=http://www.theatermania.com/off-broadway/news/the-tank-announces-new-season-home_82204.html|accessdate=August 28, 2017|work=TheaterMania|date=August 25, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828225955/http://www.theatermania.com/off-broadway/news/the-tank-announces-new-season-home_82204.html|archivedate=August 28, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"playbill new home\">{{cite news|last1=Clement|first1=Olivia|title=The Tank Finds New Home in Old Abingdon Theatre Company Space|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/the-tank-finds-new-home-in-old-abingdon-theatre-company-space|accessdate=September 14, 2017|work=[[Playbill]]|date=August 31, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914172942/http://www.playbill.com/article/the-tank-finds-new-home-in-old-abingdon-theatre-company-space|archivedate=September 14, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"vv 2017 move\">{{cite news|last1=Felton-Dansky|first1=Miriam|title=This Fall, Rent-Challenged Downtown Theaters Are Battling to Stay in Place|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2017/09/12/this-fall-rent-challenged-downtown-theaters-are-battling-to-stay-in-place/|accessdate=October 7, 2017|work=[[The Village Voice]]|date=September 12, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913052850/https://www.villagevoice.com/2017/09/12/this-fall-rent-challenged-downtown-theaters-are-battling-to-stay-in-place/|archivedate=September 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"amny\">{{cite news |last1=Stiffler |first1=Scott |title=Rising rents push NYC theater companies to get creative to secure real estate |url=https://www.amny.com/real-estate/theater-real-estate-1.35887030 |accessdate=September 6, 2019 |work=[[AM New York]] |date=September 4, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904233254/https://www.amny.com/real-estate/theater-real-estate-1.35887030 |archivedate=September 4, 2019}}</ref> The Chain Theater, Workshop Theater, and [[the Barrow Group]] also reside in the same building as The Tank.<ref name=\"amny\" /> The Tank's move coincided with the relocations of several other New York City theaters in mid-2017, including [[the Flea Theater]] and the Chocolate Factory.<ref name=\"vv 2017 move\" />\n\nIn 2020, during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]], The Tank laid off most of its staff and suspended programming beginning March 13, canceling 109 performances for an estimated loss of $50,000.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Snook |first1=Raven |title=Beyond Broadway: Which Shows Are Suspended, Permanently Closed or Still Running? |url=https://www.tdf.org/stages/article/2356/beyond-broadway-which-shows-are-suspended-permanently-closed-or-still-running |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=[[Theatre Development Fund]] |date=March 13, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314005835/https://www.tdf.org/stages/article/2356/beyond-broadway-which-shows-are-suspended-permanently-closed-or-still-running |archivedate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Helen |title='There Is No \"Surplus\" in Nonprofit': How Off Broadway Is Coping With Closure |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/there-is-no-surplus-how-off-broadway-theater-is-coping.html |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=[[Vulture.com|Vulture]] |date=March 13, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314053843/https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/there-is-no-surplus-how-off-broadway-theater-is-coping.html |archivedate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dilella |first1=Frank |title=How the Coronavirus Has Impacted Off-Broadway |url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/arts/2020/03/20/the-coronavirus-impact-on-off-broadway- |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=[[NY1]] |date=March 20, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320172526/https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/arts/2020/03/20/the-coronavirus-impact-on-off-broadway- |archivedate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> While the space is closed, The Tank launched a weekly digital arts [[Live streaming|livestream]] called CyberTank.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stigler |first1=Britt |title=The Tank launches new (digital) spaces with an excerpt from Ran Xia |url=https://allarts.org/2020/03/the-tank-launches-new-digital-spaces-with-an-excerpt-from-ran-xia/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=All Arts |publisher=[[WNET]] |date=March 18, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318172738/https://allarts.org/2020/03/the-tank-launches-new-digital-spaces-with-an-excerpt-from-ran-xia/ |archivedate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Tank's artistic director is Meghan Finn as of 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clement |first1=Olivia |title=Tonya Pinkins Curates Collection of Feminist Plays at The Tank Off-Broadway |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/tonya-pinkins-curates-collection-of-feminist-plays-at-the-tank-off-broadway |accessdate=September 6, 2019 |work=[[Playbill]] |date=September 6, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906201352/http://www.playbill.com/article/tonya-pinkins-curates-collection-of-feminist-plays-at-the-tank-off-broadway |archivedate=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n{{multiple image\n | width = \n | image1 = The Tank - 98 Seat Theater.jpg\n | alt1 = A dark proscenium stage illuminated by the glow of purple lights\n | image2 = The Tank - 56 Seat Theater.jpg\n | alt2 = A dark three-quarter blackbox theater with seats in front and to both sides, illuminated by pinkish lights\n | footer = The Tank's 98-seat proscenium stage (left) and 56-seat blackbox (right)\n}}\nCategorized as an Off-Off-Broadway venue, The Tank presents more than 800 performances each year across several disciplines.<ref name=\"open\">{{cite news|last1=Hookey|first1=Sarah|work=[[BroadwayWorld]]|title=All For One Theater premieres Crystal Skillman's Open at The Tank in June|date=March 12, 2019|accessdate=June 30, 2019|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/off-off-broadway/article/All-For-One-Theater-premieres-Crystal-Skillmans-OPEN-at-The-Tank-in-June-20190312|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630011710/https://www.broadwayworld.com/off-off-broadway/article/All-For-One-Theater-premieres-Crystal-Skillmans-OPEN-at-The-Tank-in-June-20190312|archivedate=June 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Study of Off-Off-Broadway Performance Venues|url=http://www.nyitawards.com/survey/OOBSpaceReport2.pdf|publisher=New York Innovative Theatre Foundation|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151216160155/http://www.nyitawards.com/survey/OOBSpaceReport2.pdf|archivedate=December 16, 2015|date=December 2008|accessdate=January 28, 2017|website=New York Innovative Theatre Awards}}</ref> Each discipline\u2013including dance, music, theater, comedy, and film\u2013is curated by one or more curators.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref name=\"harv\" /> Artists do not pay to use the venue and are paid a portion of the ticket sales, a practice made sustainable by surplus value generated by better-selling shows.<ref name=\"rail\" /> As a nonprofit producer, the organization relies heavily on volunteers.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref name=\"cat\">{{cite news|last1=Roberts|first1=Shoshana|title=Vera & Valya & The Magical One Cat Circus|url=http://www.theasy.com/Reviews/2016/V/veraandvalyaandthemagicalonecatcircus.php|accessdate=January 29, 2017|work=Theatre Is Easy|date=November 15, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129212200/http://www.theasy.com/Reviews/2016/V/veraandvalyaandthemagicalonecatcircus.php|archivedate=January 29, 2017}}</ref> Most days, The Tank runs multiple shows in a single night.<ref name=\"rail\" /> In addition to presenting shows at its 36th Street location, artists have also produced pieces with The Tank at other venues in New York City, such as the 3LD Art and Technology Center in Lower Manhattan and Standard ToyKraft in [[Williamsburg, Brooklyn]].<ref name=\"cat\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Brantley|first1=Ben|title=Review: Urban Nightmares as Puppets in 'The Paper Hat Game'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/27/theater/review-urban-nightmares-as-puppets-in-the-paper-hat-game.html|accessdate=January 29, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 26, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722150341/http://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/27/theater/review-urban-nightmares-as-puppets-in-the-paper-hat-game.html|archivedate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> The theater runs several festivals each summer, including LadyFest and DarkFest, the latter of which requires performers to create shows using no [[stage lighting]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vincentelli |first1=Elisabeth |title=Review: Besties With Rasputin in 'Red Emma and the Mad Monk' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/21/theater/review-red-emma-and-the-mad-monk-the-tank.html |accessdate=September 16, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 21, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830114424/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/21/theater/review-red-emma-and-the-mad-monk-the-tank.html |archivedate=August 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=van Laarhoven |first1=Kasper |title=Let There Be Dark! at This Electricity-Free Theater Festival |url=http://bedfordandbowery.com/2017/07/let-there-be-dark-at-this-electricity-free-theater-festival/ |accessdate=September 16, 2018 |work=Bedford + Bowery |publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=July 27, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018074841/http://bedfordandbowery.com/2017/07/let-there-be-dark-at-this-electricity-free-theater-festival/ |archivedate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Reception==\n''[[The Village Voice]]'' listed The Tank in its Best of NYC poll in 2004, describing the theater as the city's \"Best Broadway theater turned hipster hangout\".<ref name=\"best of nyc\">{{cite news|title=Best Broadway theater turned hipster hangout|work=[[The Village Voice]]|page=88|date=October 6\u201312, 2004|last1=Cole|first1=Lori|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041027184720/http://www.villagevoice.com/bestof/2004/detail.php?id=4452|archivedate=October 27, 2004|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/bestof/2004/detail.php?id=4452|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref> In 2020, ''[[Time Out New York]]'' described The Tank as \"one of NYC's premiere incubators of emerging talent\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Feldman |first1=Adam |title=The best live theater to watch from home on March 31 |url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/theater/the-best-live-theater-to-watch-from-home-march-31 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=[[Time Out New York]] |date=March 31, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331201548/https://www.timeout.com/newyork/theater/the-best-live-theater-to-watch-from-home-march-31 |archivedate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[A Very Merry Unauthorized Children's Scientology Pageant]]'', which premiered at The Tank in 2003, received an [[Obie Award]] special citation in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hernandez|first1=Ernio|title=''A Very Merry Unauthorized Children's Scientology Pageant'' Returns to NYC|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/a-very-merry-unauthorized-childrens-scientology-pageant-returns-to-nyc-com-134954|accessdate=October 3, 2018|work=[[Playbill]]|date=September 15, 2006|archivedate=June 30, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630052745/http://www.playbill.com/article/a-very-merry-unauthorized-childrens-scientology-pageant-returns-to-nyc-com-134954}}</ref> In 2007, [[Lucy Alibar]]'s ''Juicy and Delicious'', which would later be adapted into the film ''[[Beasts of the Southern Wild]]'', had its world premiere at The Tank.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cox |first1=Gordon |title='Beasts' author has stage roots |url=https://variety.com/2012/film/news/beasts-author-has-stage-roots-1118056553/ |accessdate=May 11, 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 14, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422153342/https://variety.com/2012/film/news/beasts-author-has-stage-roots-1118056553/ |archivedate=April 22, 2019}}</ref> Alibar's screenplay would go on to be [[List of accolades received by Beasts of the Southern Wild|nominated]] for the [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Han |first1=Angie |title=85th Academy Award Nominations: 'Beasts of the Southern Wild,' 'Lincoln,' and 'Silver Linings Playbook' Earn Major Recognition |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/85th-academy-award-nominations-beasts-of-the-southern-wild-lincoln-and-silver-linings-playbook-earn-major-recognition/ |accessdate=May 11, 2019 |work=[[/Film]] |date=January 10, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203085713/https://www.slashfilm.com/85th-academy-award-nominations-beasts-of-the-southern-wild-lincoln-and-silver-linings-playbook-earn-major-recognition/|archivedate=December 3, 2016}}</ref> The Tank has received six [[Drama Desk Award]] nominations. Two shows, ''ADA/AVA'' and ''YOUARENOWHERE'', were nominated in 2016, and another two, ''the ephemera trilogy'' and ''The Paper Hat Game'', were nominated in 2017, all in the category of [[Drama Desk Award for Unique Theatrical Experience|Unique Theatrical Experience]].<ref>{{cite news|author1=Editorial staff|title=''Shuffle Along'', ''The Humans'', and More Take Home 2016 Drama Desk Awards|url=http://www.theatermania.com/broadway/news/2016-drama-desk-award-winners_77336.html|accessdate=May 14, 2017|work=TheaterMania|date=June 5, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812083221/http://www.theatermania.com/broadway/news/2016-drama-desk-award-winners_77336.html|archivedate=August 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gerard|first1=Jeremy|title='Hello, Dolly!' And 'The Hairy Ape' Lead Drama Desk Musical, Drama Nominations|url=https://deadline.com/2017/04/hello-dolly-and-the-hairy-ape-lead-drama-desk-nominations-1202078367/|accessdate=May 14, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 27, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428110204/http://deadline.com/2017/04/hello-dolly-and-the-hairy-ape-lead-drama-desk-nominations-1202078367/|archivedate=April 28, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, [[Sinking Ship Productions]]' ''A Hunger Artist'' received two nominations: [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Solo Performance|Outstanding Solo Performance]] and Outstanding Puppet Design.<ref>{{cite web|title=2018 Nominees|url=http://dramadeskawards.com/2018-nominees|website=Drama Desk Awards|publisher=Drama Desk|accessdate=April 27, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427175821/http://dramadeskawards.com/2018-nominees|archivedate=April 27, 2018|date=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n<!--==Selected production history==-->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.thetanknyc.org/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tank, The}}\n[[Category:2003 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:Off-Off-Broadway]]\n[[Category:Theatre companies in New York City]]\n[[Category:Theatres in Manhattan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox venue\n| name                   = The Tank\n| image = The Tank exterior, September 2018.jpg\n| image_alt=A yellow brick building with two double glass doors, one to the left, the other to the right, runs out of the frame at the top. A person is entering through the left glass doors. A black and white banner hangs from the second story with The Tank's logo and the words \"THE TANK\".\n| image_caption= The Tank's entrance (left), 2018\n| logo_image             = The Tank logo.jpg\n| logo_caption           = The Tank's logo\n| address                = 312 West 36th Street, Manhattan, New York\n| coordinates            = {{Coord|40.7535298|-73.9932606|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} \n| type                   = [[Off-Off-Broadway]]\n| genre                  = Dance, theater, music, film, comedy\n| opened                 = {{Start date|2003|05}} \n| website                =  {{URL|thetanknyc.org}}\n}}\n'''The Tank''' is a nonprofit [[Off-Off-Broadway]] performance venue and producer in Manhattan, New York. The organization was founded in May 2003 and has since moved several times, currently residing on 36th Street. The Tank presents art across several disciplines (comedy, dance, theater, music, film), produced at no fee for use of the venue to the presenting artists. In addition to its space in Manhattan, The Tank produces shows performed elsewhere throughout New York City, collectively presenting over 800 performances each year. Programming at the theater is currently suspended due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].\n\n==History==\nThe Tank was founded in May 2003 in [[Manhattan]], New York, by eight artists, all recent college graduates in their mid-20s.<ref name=\"rail\">{{cite news|last1=Hodges|first1=Mary Love|title=Spotlight on The Tank|url=http://brooklynrail.org/2010/02/dance/spotlight-on-the-tank|accessdate=January 27, 2017|work=[[The Brooklyn Rail]]|date=February 3, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512063126/http://brooklynrail.org/2010/02/dance/spotlight-on-the-tank|archivedate=May 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"harv\">{{cite news|last1=Lambert|first1=Craig|title=Avant-Garde Incubator|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/2007/03/avant-garde-incubator.html|accessdate=January 28, 2017|work=[[Harvard Magazine]]|date=March\u2013April 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809010232/http://harvardmagazine.com/2007/03/avant-garde-incubator.html|archivedate=August 9, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"spirit\">{{cite news|title=Downtown Edge in Midtown Venue|last1=Eichna|first1=Charlotte|work=West Side Spirit|date=June 17, 2004|page=26}}</ref> Its founders, mostly graduates of [[Yale University]], [[Oberlin College]], and [[Harvard University]], included playwright [[Amy Herzog]], playwright and director [[Alex Timbers]], Justin Krebs, Rachel Levy, Mike Rosenthal, and Randy Bell, who collectively expressed the goal of offering young artists across disciplines the space to create work in the center of New York City.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref name=\"harv\" /><ref name=\"spirit\" /><ref name=\"theasy2013\">{{cite news|title=The Tank: A Theasy Interview with Josh Luxenberg, curator of the Flint & Tinder theater series at The Tank|url=http://www.theasy.com/FeaturedArtist/thetank.php|accessdate=January 27, 2017|work=Theatre Is Easy|date=June 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151013063555/http://www.theasy.com/FeaturedArtist/thetank.php|archivedate=October 13, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"trib\">{{cite news|title=Subterranean 'Tank' Hosts New Music|last1=Pinto|first1=Nick|page=43|date=February 2008|work=[[The Tribeca Trib]]|accessdate=June 27, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908003153/http://www.tribecatrib.com/news/newsfeb08/Tank.html|url=http://www.tribecatrib.com/news/newsfeb08/Tank.html|archivedate=September 8, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe organization was first housed on [[42nd Street (Manhattan)|42nd Street]] between [[Ninth Avenue (Manhattan)|Ninth]] and [[Tenth Avenue (Manhattan)|Tenth]] Avenues.<ref name=\"spirit\" /> The Tank leased the space on a month-to-month basis from a landlord who intended to sell the building in which the theater was housed, and within 10 months, they had repaid their startup loans. The company derived its name from the architecture of its first space: three large windows overlooking 42nd Street led to someone calling the space The Fishtank and later the ''Fish'' was dropped in favor of The Tank.<ref name=\"harv\" /><ref name=\"spirit\" /> By 2006, the company had moved twice and by 2007, it had won an unsolicited grant of $10,000 from the [[Carnegie Corporation of New York]] and was receiving money from the Lower Manhattan Cultural Council.<ref name=\"harv\" /> The Tank's third location, into which it moved in 2006, was on [[Church Street (Manhattan)|Church Street]] in the [[Tribeca]] neighborhood, where the organization shared space with [[Collective:Unconscious]] as late as 2008.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref name=\"harv\" /><ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Williams|editor1-first=James R.|title=Inside New York 2008|date=2007|publisher=Inside New York|location=New York City|isbn=978-1892768407|page=158|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZtY1xdbFJz0C&pg=PA158}}</ref>\n\nBy 2010, The Tank had returned to Manhattan's midtown [[Theater District, Manhattan|Theater District]], occupying the [[Davenport Theatre]] on 45th Street between [[Eighth Avenue (Manhattan)|Eighth]] and Ninth Avenues.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=La Rocco |first1=Claudia |title=A Long Swim Looking for Laughs |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/06/theater/reviews/the-umbrella-plays-at-the-tank.html |accessdate=March 27, 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 5, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328001030/https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/06/theater/reviews/the-umbrella-plays-at-the-tank.html |archivedate=March 28, 2019}}</ref> The Tank had moved to 46th Street by 2013, where it resided until 2017.<ref name=\"theasy2013\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Heins|first1=Scott|title=5 Fun Things To Do In NYC This Week|url=http://gothamist.com/2017/01/16/5_things_jan_2017.php|accessdate=January 28, 2017|work=[[Gothamist]]|date=January 16, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129015925/http://gothamist.com/2017/01/16/5_things_jan_2017.php|archivedate=January 29, 2017}}</ref> That year, The Tank signed a ten-year, $18,000/month lease on and moved to a two-stage venue on 36th Street, the former home of Abingdon Theatre Company, with one 56-seat [[black box theater]] and one 98-seat [[Proscenium|proscenium theater]].<ref name=\"tm move\">{{cite news|last1=Fujishima|first1=Kenji|title=The Tank Announces New Season, New Home|url=http://www.theatermania.com/off-broadway/news/the-tank-announces-new-season-home_82204.html|accessdate=August 28, 2017|work=TheaterMania|date=August 25, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828225955/http://www.theatermania.com/off-broadway/news/the-tank-announces-new-season-home_82204.html|archivedate=August 28, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"playbill new home\">{{cite news|last1=Clement|first1=Olivia|title=The Tank Finds New Home in Old Abingdon Theatre Company Space|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/the-tank-finds-new-home-in-old-abingdon-theatre-company-space|accessdate=September 14, 2017|work=[[Playbill]]|date=August 31, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914172942/http://www.playbill.com/article/the-tank-finds-new-home-in-old-abingdon-theatre-company-space|archivedate=September 14, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"vv 2017 move\">{{cite news|last1=Felton-Dansky|first1=Miriam|title=This Fall, Rent-Challenged Downtown Theaters Are Battling to Stay in Place|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2017/09/12/this-fall-rent-challenged-downtown-theaters-are-battling-to-stay-in-place/|accessdate=October 7, 2017|work=[[The Village Voice]]|date=September 12, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913052850/https://www.villagevoice.com/2017/09/12/this-fall-rent-challenged-downtown-theaters-are-battling-to-stay-in-place/|archivedate=September 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"amny\">{{cite news |last1=Stiffler |first1=Scott |title=Rising rents push NYC theater companies to get creative to secure real estate |url=https://www.amny.com/real-estate/theater-real-estate-1.35887030 |accessdate=September 6, 2019 |work=[[AM New York]] |date=September 4, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904233254/https://www.amny.com/real-estate/theater-real-estate-1.35887030 |archivedate=September 4, 2019}}</ref> The Chain Theater, Workshop Theater, and [[the Barrow Group]] also reside in the same building as The Tank.<ref name=\"amny\" /> The Tank's move coincided with the relocations of several other New York City theaters in mid-2017, including [[the Flea Theater]] and the Chocolate Factory.<ref name=\"vv 2017 move\" />\n\nIn 2020, during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]], The Tank laid off most of its staff and suspended programming beginning March 13, canceling 109 performances for an estimated loss of $50,000.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Snook |first1=Raven |title=Beyond Broadway: Which Shows Are Suspended, Permanently Closed or Still Running? |url=https://www.tdf.org/stages/article/2356/beyond-broadway-which-shows-are-suspended-permanently-closed-or-still-running |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=[[Theatre Development Fund]] |date=March 13, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314005835/https://www.tdf.org/stages/article/2356/beyond-broadway-which-shows-are-suspended-permanently-closed-or-still-running |archivedate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Helen |title='There Is No \"Surplus\" in Nonprofit': How Off Broadway Is Coping With Closure |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/there-is-no-surplus-how-off-broadway-theater-is-coping.html |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=[[Vulture.com|Vulture]] |date=March 13, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314053843/https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/there-is-no-surplus-how-off-broadway-theater-is-coping.html |archivedate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dilella |first1=Frank |title=How the Coronavirus Has Impacted Off-Broadway |url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/arts/2020/03/20/the-coronavirus-impact-on-off-broadway- |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=[[NY1]] |date=March 20, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320172526/https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/arts/2020/03/20/the-coronavirus-impact-on-off-broadway- |archivedate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> While the space is closed, The Tank launched a weekly digital arts [[Live streaming|livestream]] called CyberTank.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stigler |first1=Britt |title=The Tank launches new (digital) spaces with an excerpt from Ran Xia |url=https://allarts.org/2020/03/the-tank-launches-new-digital-spaces-with-an-excerpt-from-ran-xia/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=All Arts |publisher=[[WNET]] |date=March 18, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318172738/https://allarts.org/2020/03/the-tank-launches-new-digital-spaces-with-an-excerpt-from-ran-xia/ |archivedate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Tank's artistic director is Meghan Finn as of 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clement |first1=Olivia |title=Tonya Pinkins Curates Collection of Feminist Plays at The Tank Off-Broadway |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/tonya-pinkins-curates-collection-of-feminist-plays-at-the-tank-off-broadway |accessdate=September 6, 2019 |work=[[Playbill]] |date=September 6, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906201352/http://www.playbill.com/article/tonya-pinkins-curates-collection-of-feminist-plays-at-the-tank-off-broadway |archivedate=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n{{multiple image\n | width = \n | image1 = The Tank - 98 Seat Theater.jpg\n | alt1 = A dark proscenium stage illuminated by the glow of purple lights\n | image2 = The Tank - 56 Seat Theater.jpg\n | alt2 = A dark three-quarter blackbox theater with seats in front and to both sides, illuminated by pinkish lights\n | footer = The Tank's 98-seat proscenium stage (left) and 56-seat blackbox (right)\n}}\nCategorized as an Off-Off-Broadway venue, The Tank presents more than 800 performances each year across several disciplines.<ref name=\"open\">{{cite news|last1=Hookey|first1=Sarah|work=[[BroadwayWorld]]|title=All For One Theater premieres Crystal Skillman's Open at The Tank in June|date=March 12, 2019|accessdate=June 30, 2019|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/off-off-broadway/article/All-For-One-Theater-premieres-Crystal-Skillmans-OPEN-at-The-Tank-in-June-20190312|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630011710/https://www.broadwayworld.com/off-off-broadway/article/All-For-One-Theater-premieres-Crystal-Skillmans-OPEN-at-The-Tank-in-June-20190312|archivedate=June 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Study of Off-Off-Broadway Performance Venues|url=http://www.nyitawards.com/survey/OOBSpaceReport2.pdf|publisher=New York Innovative Theatre Foundation|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151216160155/http://www.nyitawards.com/survey/OOBSpaceReport2.pdf|archivedate=December 16, 2015|date=December 2008|accessdate=January 28, 2017|website=New York Innovative Theatre Awards}}</ref> Each discipline\u2013including dance, music, theater, comedy, and film\u2013is curated by one or more curators.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref name=\"harv\" /> Artists do not pay to use the venue and are paid a portion of the ticket sales, a practice made sustainable by surplus value generated by better-selling shows.<ref name=\"rail\" /> As a nonprofit producer, the organization relies heavily on volunteers.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref name=\"cat\">{{cite news|last1=Roberts|first1=Shoshana|title=Vera & Valya & The Magical One Cat Circus|url=http://www.theasy.com/Reviews/2016/V/veraandvalyaandthemagicalonecatcircus.php|accessdate=January 29, 2017|work=Theatre Is Easy|date=November 15, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129212200/http://www.theasy.com/Reviews/2016/V/veraandvalyaandthemagicalonecatcircus.php|archivedate=January 29, 2017}}</ref> Most days, The Tank runs multiple shows in a single night.<ref name=\"rail\" /> In addition to presenting shows at its 36th Street location, artists have also produced pieces with The Tank at other venues in New York City, such as the 3LD Art and Technology Center in Lower Manhattan and Standard ToyKraft in [[Williamsburg, Brooklyn]].<ref name=\"cat\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Brantley|first1=Ben|title=Review: Urban Nightmares as Puppets in 'The Paper Hat Game'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/27/theater/review-urban-nightmares-as-puppets-in-the-paper-hat-game.html|accessdate=January 29, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 26, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722150341/http://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/27/theater/review-urban-nightmares-as-puppets-in-the-paper-hat-game.html|archivedate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> The theater runs several festivals each summer, including LadyFest and DarkFest, the latter of which requires performers to create shows using no [[stage lighting]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vincentelli |first1=Elisabeth |title=Review: Besties With Rasputin in 'Red Emma and the Mad Monk' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/21/theater/review-red-emma-and-the-mad-monk-the-tank.html |accessdate=September 16, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 21, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830114424/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/21/theater/review-red-emma-and-the-mad-monk-the-tank.html |archivedate=August 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=van Laarhoven |first1=Kasper |title=Let There Be Dark! at This Electricity-Free Theater Festival |url=http://bedfordandbowery.com/2017/07/let-there-be-dark-at-this-electricity-free-theater-festival/ |accessdate=September 16, 2018 |work=Bedford + Bowery |publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=July 27, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018074841/http://bedfordandbowery.com/2017/07/let-there-be-dark-at-this-electricity-free-theater-festival/ |archivedate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Reception==\n''[[The Village Voice]]'' listed The Tank in its Best of NYC poll in 2004, describing the theater as the city's \"Best Broadway theater turned hipster hangout\".<ref name=\"best of nyc\">{{cite news|title=Best Broadway theater turned hipster hangout|work=[[The Village Voice]]|page=88|date=October 6\u201312, 2004|last1=Cole|first1=Lori|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041027184720/http://www.villagevoice.com/bestof/2004/detail.php?id=4452|archivedate=October 27, 2004|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/bestof/2004/detail.php?id=4452|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref> In 2020, ''[[Time Out New York]]'' described The Tank as \"one of NYC's premiere incubators of emerging talent\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Feldman |first1=Adam |title=The best live theater to watch from home on March 31 |url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/theater/the-best-live-theater-to-watch-from-home-march-31 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=[[Time Out New York]] |date=March 31, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331201548/https://www.timeout.com/newyork/theater/the-best-live-theater-to-watch-from-home-march-31 |archivedate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[A Very Merry Unauthorized Children's Scientology Pageant]]'', which premiered at The Tank in 2003, received an [[Obie Award]] special citation in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hernandez|first1=Ernio|title=''A Very Merry Unauthorized Children's Scientology Pageant'' Returns to NYC|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/a-very-merry-unauthorized-childrens-scientology-pageant-returns-to-nyc-com-134954|accessdate=October 3, 2018|work=[[Playbill]]|date=September 15, 2006|archivedate=June 30, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630052745/http://www.playbill.com/article/a-very-merry-unauthorized-childrens-scientology-pageant-returns-to-nyc-com-134954}}</ref> In 2007, [[Lucy Alibar]]'s ''Juicy and Delicious'', which would later be adapted into the film ''[[Beasts of the Southern Wild]]'', had its world premiere at The Tank.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cox |first1=Gordon |title='Beasts' author has stage roots |url=https://variety.com/2012/film/news/beasts-author-has-stage-roots-1118056553/ |accessdate=May 11, 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 14, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422153342/https://variety.com/2012/film/news/beasts-author-has-stage-roots-1118056553/ |archivedate=April 22, 2019}}</ref> Alibar's screenplay would go on to be [[List of accolades received by Beasts of the Southern Wild|nominated]] for the [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Han |first1=Angie |title=85th Academy Award Nominations: 'Beasts of the Southern Wild,' 'Lincoln,' and 'Silver Linings Playbook' Earn Major Recognition |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/85th-academy-award-nominations-beasts-of-the-southern-wild-lincoln-and-silver-linings-playbook-earn-major-recognition/ |accessdate=May 11, 2019 |work=[[/Film]] |date=January 10, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203085713/https://www.slashfilm.com/85th-academy-award-nominations-beasts-of-the-southern-wild-lincoln-and-silver-linings-playbook-earn-major-recognition/|archivedate=December 3, 2016}}</ref> The Tank has received six [[Drama Desk Award]] nominations. Two shows, ''ADA/AVA'' and ''YOUARENOWHERE'', were nominated in 2016, and another two, ''the ephemera trilogy'' and ''The Paper Hat Game'', were nominated in 2017, all in the category of [[Drama Desk Award for Unique Theatrical Experience|Unique Theatrical Experience]].<ref>{{cite news|author1=Editorial staff|title=''Shuffle Along'', ''The Humans'', and More Take Home 2016 Drama Desk Awards|url=http://www.theatermania.com/broadway/news/2016-drama-desk-award-winners_77336.html|accessdate=May 14, 2017|work=TheaterMania|date=June 5, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812083221/http://www.theatermania.com/broadway/news/2016-drama-desk-award-winners_77336.html|archivedate=August 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gerard|first1=Jeremy|title='Hello, Dolly!' And 'The Hairy Ape' Lead Drama Desk Musical, Drama Nominations|url=https://deadline.com/2017/04/hello-dolly-and-the-hairy-ape-lead-drama-desk-nominations-1202078367/|accessdate=May 14, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 27, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428110204/http://deadline.com/2017/04/hello-dolly-and-the-hairy-ape-lead-drama-desk-nominations-1202078367/|archivedate=April 28, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, [[Sinking Ship Productions]]' ''A Hunger Artist'' received two nominations: [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Solo Performance|Outstanding Solo Performance]] and Outstanding Puppet Design.<ref>{{cite web|title=2018 Nominees|url=http://dramadeskawards.com/2018-nominees|website=Drama Desk Awards|publisher=Drama Desk|accessdate=April 27, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427175821/http://dramadeskawards.com/2018-nominees|archivedate=April 27, 2018|date=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n<!--==Selected production history==-->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.thetanknyc.org/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tank, The}}\n[[Category:2003 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:Off-Off-Broadway]]\n[[Category:Theatre companies in New York City]]\n[[Category:Theatres in Manhattan]]\n", "name_user": "Bobamnertiopsis", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:tense", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Tank_(theater)"}
{"title_page": "Andrew J. Applegate", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name                = Andrew J. Applegate\n|image               = \n|imagesize           =  \n|smallimage          = \n|caption             = \n|order               = 1st [[Lieutenant Governor of Alabama]]\n|term_start          = July 24, 1868\n|term_end            = November 26, 1870\n|governor            = [[William Hugh Smith]]\n|predecessor         = \n|successor           = [[Edward H. Moren]]\n|birth_date          = {{birth date|1833|10|14}}\n|birth_place         = [[Georgetown, Ohio]]\n|death_date          = {{death date and age|1870|8|21|1833|10|14}}\n|death_place         = [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]]\n|constituency        = \n|party               = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse              = \n|children            = \n|profession          = \n|religion            = \n|signature           = \n|footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Andrew J. Applegate''' (October 14, 1833 \u2013 August 21, 1870) was the [[List of Lieutenant Governors of Alabama|first Lieutenant Governor]] of [[Alabama]], serving during [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]]. A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], Applegate served Governor [[William Hugh Smith|William H. Smith]] of the same political party, from 1868\u20131870.\n\nA son of Benjamin and Rebecca Applegate, he grew up on a farm near [[Georgetown, Ohio|Georgetown]], [[Ohio]]. His father's family had emigrated from [[Holland]], settling in  [[Pennsylvania]] and then [[Kentucky]], until finally moving to Ohio. Applegate was educated within the [[Public school (government funded)|public school]]s at Georgetown, where he later studied and practiced [[law]]. During the [[American Civil War]], Applegate enlisted for one year on July 9, 1861, as a [[wagon]]er in the Fourth Independent Company, Ohio Cavalry, but soon became its [[quartermaster sergeant]]. In April 1865, he was commissioned [[Captain (United States)|captain]] of Company H, [[189th Ohio Infantry]]. Too late to see action, his regiment was sent to Alabama to serve on occupation duty.\n\nAfter his discharge, Applegate returned home for his family and moved to [[Huntsville, Alabama]], to open his law practice. In 1867, he was elected as a Radical Republican to serve as a member of the Constitutional Convention to frame a new State [[constitution]]. In the election under that constitution, Applegate was Alabama's first and only elected lieutenant governor on August 13, 1868. He moved to Mobile and served Alabama two years as lieutenant governor. He died of mysterious causes in Chattanooga two years later.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.archives.state.al.us/conoff/Applegat.html Biography courtesy of the Alabama Department of Archives]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off|us}}\n{{Succession box\n| before= ''Title established''\n|title= [[Lieutenant Governor of Alabama]]\n|years=1868\u20131870 \n|after=[[Edward H. Moren]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{AlabamaLtGovernors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Applegate, Andrew J.}}\n[[Category:Lieutenant Governors of Alabama]]\n[[Category:1833 births]]\n[[Category:1870 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Georgetown, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Huntsville, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Quartermasters]]\n[[Category:Alabama Republicans]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:People of Ohio in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Radical Republican Party politicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Huntsville, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Huntsville, Alabama]]\n[[Category:People who died in office]]\n\n{{alabama-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name                = Andrew J. Applegate\n|image               = \n|imagesize           =  \n|smallimage          = \n|caption             = \n|order               = 1st [[Lieutenant Governor of Alabama]]\n|term_start          = July 24, 1868\n|term_end            = November 26, 1870\n|governor            = [[William Hugh Smith]]\n|predecessor         = \n|successor           = [[Edward H. Moren]]\n|birth_date          = {{birth date|1833|10|14}}\n|birth_place         = [[Georgetown, Ohio]]\n|death_date          = {{death date and age|1870|8|21|1833|10|14}}\n|death_place         = [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]]\n|constituency        = \n|party               = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse              = \n|children            = \n|profession          = \n|religion            = \n|signature           = \n|footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Andrew J. Applegate''' (October 14, 1833 \u2013 August 21, 1870) was the [[List of Lieutenant Governors of Alabama|first Lieutenant Governor]] of [[Alabama]], serving during [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]]. A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], Applegate served Governor [[William Hugh Smith|William H. Smith]] of the same political party, from 1868-1870.\n\nA son of Benjamin and Rebecca Applegate, he grew up on a farm near [[Georgetown, Ohio|Georgetown]], [[Ohio]]. His father's family had emigrated from [[Holland]], settling in  [[Pennsylvania]] and then [[Kentucky]], until finally moving to Ohio. Applegate was educated within the [[Public school (government funded)|public school]]s at Georgetown, where he later studied and practiced [[law]]. During the [[American Civil War]], Applegate enlisted for one year on July 9, 1861, as a [[wagon]]er in the Fourth Independent Company, Ohio Cavalry, but soon became its [[quartermaster sergeant]]. In April 1865, he was commissioned [[Captain (United States)|captain]] of Company H, [[189th Ohio Infantry]]. Too late to see action, his regiment was sent to Alabama to serve on occupation duty.\n\nAfter his discharge, Applegate returned home for his family and moved to [[Huntsville, Alabama]], to open his law practice. In 1867, he was elected as a Radical Republican to serve as a member of the Constitutional Convention to frame a new State [[constitution]]. In the election under that constitution, Applegate was Alabama's first and only elected lieutenant governor on August 13, 1868. He moved to Mobile and served Alabama two years as lieutenant governor. He died of mysterious causes in Chattanooga two years later.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.archives.state.al.us/conoff/Applegat.html Biography courtesy of the Alabama Department of Archives]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off|us}}\n{{Succession box\n| before= ''Title established''\n|title= [[Lieutenant Governor of Alabama]]\n|years=1868\u20131870 \n|after=[[Edward H. Moren]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{AlabamaLtGovernors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Applegate, Andrew J.}}\n[[Category:Lieutenant Governors of Alabama]]\n[[Category:1833 births]]\n[[Category:1870 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Georgetown, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Huntsville, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Quartermasters]]\n[[Category:Alabama Republicans]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:People of Ohio in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Radical Republican Party politicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Huntsville, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Huntsville, Alabama]]\n[[Category:People who died in office]]\n\n{{alabama-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1868-1870 \u2192 1868\u20131870", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_J._Applegate"}
{"title_page": "Ellen Sullivan Woodward", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ellen Sullivan Woodward\n| image       = Ellen_S._Woodward,_1887-1971.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = July 11, 1887\n| birth_place = Oxford, Mississippi\n| death_date =  September 23, 1971\n| death_place = Washington, D.C.\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = New Deal work programs for women\n| occupation  = Government administrator\n| nationality = \n}}\n\n'''Ellen Sullivan Woodward''' was a federal civil servant and state legislator. She served as director of work relief programs for women organized as part of the [[Presidency of Franklin D. Roosevelt | Roosevelt]] administration's [[New Deal]]  in the 1930s.\n\nThe daughter of [[William Van Amberg Sullivan]], an attorney who later served as a congressman from Mississippi and United States senator, and Belle Murray Sullivan, she was born in [[Oxford, Mississippi]]. She was educated in Oxford and in [[Washington, D.C.]].<ref name=mississippi>{{cite web |url=https://mississippiencyclopedia.org/entries/ellen-sullivan-woodward/ |title=Ellen Sullivan Woodward |work=Mississippi Encyclopedia |last=Swain |first=Martha |accessdate=November 18, 2018 |publisher=Center for Study of Southern Culture |date=July 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1906, she married Albert Y. Woodward, an attorney; the couple had one son. Her husband served in the [[Mississippi House of Representatives]]. When he died in 1925, she was elected to serve the remainder of his term, becoming the second woman to serve as a representative for the state.<ref name=mississippi/>\n\nWoodward did not run for reelection. She became director of civic development for the Mississippi State Board of Development, serving as executive director for the board from 1929 to 1933. She was also a delegate to the [[1928 Democratic National Convention]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/notableamericanw00sich |url-access=registration |title=Notable American Women: The Modern Period : a Biographical Dictionary |publisher=Harvard University Press |pages=[https://archive.org/details/notableamericanw00sich/page/747 747]\u201348 |first=Barbara |last=Sicherman |author2=Green, Carol Hurd |year=1980 |isbn=978-0674627338}}</ref> \n\nShe was director of the Women's Division of the [[Federal Emergency Relief Administration]] (FERA) from 1933 to 1935; director of the Women's and Professional Projects of the [[Works Progress Administration]] (WPA) from 1935 to 1938; and a member of the three-member [[Social Security Administration | Social Security]] Board from 1938 to 1946. She served in advisory roles to the [[United Nations Relief and Rehabilitation Administration]] (UNRRA) and the [[United Nations Economic and Social Council]].<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Greenwood Publishing Group| isbn = 978-0-313-30618-1| last = Olson| first = James Stuart| title = Historical Dictionary of the Great Depression, 1929-1940| date = 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn 1947 the Women's College of the University of North Carolina awarded Woodward an honorary degree in recognition of her dedication to public welfare in Mississippi, social security in the nation, and domestic and international relief efforts.<ref>*{{Cite web| title = Woodward, Ellen Sullivan (1887\u20131971) {{!}} Encyclopedia.com| accessdate = 2018-10-29| url = https://www.encyclopedia.com/women/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/woodward-ellen-sullivan-1887-1971}}</ref>\n\nIn 1946, Woodward was named director of a division in the newly created [[Federal Security Agency]]; she retired in December 1953. She died in Washington at the age of 84.<ref name=mississippi/>\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{Cite journal| volume = 15| issue = 4| pages = 201\u2013213| last = Swain| first = Martha| title = \"The Forgotten Woman': Ellen S. Woodward and Women's Relief in the New Deal| journal = Prologue| date = 1983}}\n*{{Cite web| title = Women's Work Relief in the Great\u00a0Depression {{!}} Mississippi History Now| accessdate = 2018-10-29| url = http://mshistorynow.mdah.state.ms.us/articles/251/womens-work-relief-in-the-great-depression}}\n*{{Cite book| publisher = Harvard University Press| isbn = 978-0-674-62733-8| last1 = Sicherman| first1 = Barbara| last2 = Green| first2 = Carol Hurd| title = Notable American Women: The Modern Period : a Biographical Dictionary| date = 1980| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/notableamericanw00sich_0}}\n*{{Cite web| title = Collection: Papers of Ellen Sullivan Woodward, 1927-1954 |accessdate = 2018-11-17| url = https://hollisarchives.lib.harvard.edu/repositories/8/resources/5763}}\n*{{Cite journal| issn = 0360-4918| volume = 20| issue = 4| pages = 707\u2013717| last = Seeber| first = Frances M.| title = Eleanor Roosevelt and Women in the New Deal: A Network of Friends| journal = Presidential Studies Quarterly| date = 1990| jstor = 20700155}}\n*{{Cite book| publisher = University Press of Mississippi| isbn = 978-0-87805-756-6| last = Swain| first = Martha H.| title = Ellen S. Woodward: New Deal advocate for women| location = Jackson| series = Twentieth-century America series| date = 1995}}\n*{{Cite book| publisher = Harvard University Press| isbn = 978-0-674-06922-0| last = Ware| first = Susan| title = Beyond Suffrage: Women in the New Deal| date = 1981}}\n*{{Cite journal| volume = 17| last = Ware| first = Susan| title = Women and the Great Depression| journal = History Now| date = 2009 | url = https://cpb-us-e1.wpmucdn.com/blogs.uoregon.edu/dist/7/11428/files/2017/03/Ware-Women-and-the-Great-Depression-wtw4tk.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118035312/https://cpb-us-e1.wpmucdn.com/blogs.uoregon.edu/dist/7/11428/files/2017/03/Ware-Women-and-the-Great-Depression-wtw4tk.pdf |archivedate=2018-11-18}}\n*{{Cite news| pages = C8| title = Ellen S. Woodward, 84, New Deal Relief Official| work = Washington Post| date = 1971-09-24}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://livingnewdeal.org/glossary/ellen-woodward-1887-1971/ The Living New Deal - Ellen Woodward (1887-1971)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Woodward, Ellen Sullivan}}\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:People of the New Deal arts projects]]\n[[Category:Works Progress Administration administrators]]\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Mississippi House of Representatives]]\n\n{{Women-hist-stub}} \n{{US-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ellen Sullivan Woodward\n| image       = Ellen_S._Woodward,_1887-1971.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = July 11, 1887\n| birth_place = Oxford, Mississippi\n| death_date =  September 23, 1971\n| death_place = Washington, D.C.\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = New Deal work programs for women\n| occupation  = Government administrator\n| nationality = \n}}\n\n'''Ellen Sullivan Woodward''' was a federal civil servant and state legislator. She served as director of work relief programs for women organized as part of the [[Presidency of Franklin D. Roosevelt | Roosevelt]] administration's [[New Deal]]  in the 1930s.\n\nThe daughter of [[William Van Amberg Sullivan]], an attorney who later served as a congressman from Mississippi and United States senator, and Belle Murray Sullivan, she was born in [[Oxford, Mississippi]]. She was educated in Oxford and in [[Washington, D.C.]].<ref name=mississippi>{{cite web |url=https://mississippiencyclopedia.org/entries/ellen-sullivan-woodward/ |title=Ellen Sullivan Woodward |work=Mississippi Encyclopedia |last=Swain |first=Martha |accessdate=November 18, 2018 |publisher=Center for Study of Southern Culture |date=July 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1906, she married Albert Y. Woodward, an attorney; the couple had one son. Her husband served in the [[Mississippi House of Representatives]]. When he died in 1925, she was elected to serve the remainder of his term, becoming the second woman to serve as a representative for the state.<ref name=mississippi/>\n\nWoodward did not run for reelection. She became director of civic development for the Mississippi State Board of Development, serving as executive director for the board from 1929 to 1933. She was also a delegate to the [[1928 Democratic National Convention]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/notableamericanw00sich |url-access=registration |title=Notable American Women: The Modern Period : a Biographical Dictionary |publisher=Harvard University Press |pages=[https://archive.org/details/notableamericanw00sich/page/747 747]\u201348 |first=Barbara |last=Sicherman |author2=Green, Carol Hurd |year=1980 |isbn=978-0674627338}}</ref> \n\nShe was director of the Women\u2019s Division of the [[Federal Emergency Relief Administration]] (FERA) from 1933 to 1935; director of the Women\u2019s and Professional Projects of the [[Works Progress Administration]] (WPA) from 1935 to 1938; and a member of the three-member [[Social Security Administration | Social Security]] Board from 1938 to 1946. She served in advisory roles to the [[United Nations Relief and Rehabilitation Administration]] (UNRRA) and the [[United Nations Economic and Social Council]].<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Greenwood Publishing Group| isbn = 978-0-313-30618-1| last = Olson| first = James Stuart| title = Historical Dictionary of the Great Depression, 1929-1940| date = 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn 1947 the Women's College of the University of North Carolina awarded Woodward an honorary degree in recognition of her dedication to public welfare in Mississippi, social security in the nation, and domestic and international relief efforts.<ref>*{{Cite web| title = Woodward, Ellen Sullivan (1887\u20131971) {{!}} Encyclopedia.com| accessdate = 2018-10-29| url = https://www.encyclopedia.com/women/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/woodward-ellen-sullivan-1887-1971}}</ref>\n\nIn 1946, Woodward was named director of a division in the newly created [[Federal Security Agency]]; she retired in December 1953. She died in Washington at the age of 84.<ref name=mississippi/>\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{Cite journal| volume = 15| issue = 4| pages = 201\u2013213| last = Swain| first = Martha| title = \"The Forgotten Woman': Ellen S. Woodward and Women's Relief in the New Deal| journal = Prologue| date = 1983}}\n*{{Cite web| title = Women's Work Relief in the Great\u00a0Depression {{!}} Mississippi History Now| accessdate = 2018-10-29| url = http://mshistorynow.mdah.state.ms.us/articles/251/womens-work-relief-in-the-great-depression}}\n*{{Cite book| publisher = Harvard University Press| isbn = 978-0-674-62733-8| last1 = Sicherman| first1 = Barbara| last2 = Green| first2 = Carol Hurd| title = Notable American Women: The Modern Period : a Biographical Dictionary| date = 1980| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/notableamericanw00sich_0}}\n*{{Cite web| title = Collection: Papers of Ellen Sullivan Woodward, 1927-1954 |accessdate = 2018-11-17| url = https://hollisarchives.lib.harvard.edu/repositories/8/resources/5763}}\n*{{Cite journal| issn = 0360-4918| volume = 20| issue = 4| pages = 707\u2013717| last = Seeber| first = Frances M.| title = Eleanor Roosevelt and Women in the New Deal: A Network of Friends| journal = Presidential Studies Quarterly| date = 1990| jstor = 20700155}}\n*{{Cite book| publisher = University Press of Mississippi| isbn = 978-0-87805-756-6| last = Swain| first = Martha H.| title = Ellen S. Woodward: New Deal advocate for women| location = Jackson| series = Twentieth-century America series| date = 1995}}\n*{{Cite book| publisher = Harvard University Press| isbn = 978-0-674-06922-0| last = Ware| first = Susan| title = Beyond Suffrage: Women in the New Deal| date = 1981}}\n*{{Cite journal| volume = 17| last = Ware| first = Susan| title = Women and the Great Depression| journal = History Now| date = 2009 | url = https://cpb-us-e1.wpmucdn.com/blogs.uoregon.edu/dist/7/11428/files/2017/03/Ware-Women-and-the-Great-Depression-